stereotype of South Vietnam that appears in most writings, both academic and popular, focuses on the first two periods to portray a caricature of a corrupt, unstable dictatorship and ignores what was achieved during the last eight years.The essays in Voices from the Second Republic of South Vietnam (1967–1975) come from those who strove to build a constitutional structure of representative government during a war for survival with a totalitarian state. Those committed to realizing a noncommunist Vietnamese future placed their hopes in the Second Republic, fought for it, and worked for its success. This book is a step in making their stories known.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aVietnam War, 1961-1975vPersonal narratives. 4aAsian Studies. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aVietnam. 7aHISTORY / Asia / Southeast Asia.2bisacsh1 aBich, Nguyen Ngoc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCuong, Nguyen Duc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDiem, Bui, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKy-Thoai, Ho van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLu, Lan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMinh, Tran Quang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSon, Tran Van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTam, Phan Cong, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTaylor, K. W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTaylor, K. W., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aTue, Phan Quang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aXai, Ma, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook 